 \nabla \times \nabla \times X - \lambda X = 0 \quad \text{ in } V \\ (\nabla \times X )\times n = 0\quad \text{ on } S 
 \int_V \nabla \times \nabla \times X \cdot Y = \underbrace{\int_V  \nabla \times X \cdot\nabla \times Y}_{\text{This term vanishes if } Y=\nabla \phi } - \int_S (\nabla \times X )\times n\cdot Y\,dS. 
 - \int_S (\nabla \times X )\times n\cdot \nabla \phi\,dS = \int_V \nabla \times \nabla \times X \cdot \nabla \phi = \int_V\lambda X \cdot \nabla \phi, 
 \int_V \lambda X \cdot \nabla \phi = \underbrace{- \int_V \nabla \cdot (\lambda X) \,\phi}_{\text{This term vanishes because } \lambda X = \nabla \times \nabla \times X} + \int_S \lambda X \cdot n\, \phi\,dS. 
 \lambda\int_S X \cdot n\, \phi\,dS = - \int_S (\nabla \times X )\times n\cdot \nabla \phi\,dS. 
